  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & What This Model Misses</h2>
  <p>No model is perfect. Here's what could skew our valuation.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>DRIVE Execution:</strong> If FedEx's network consolidation program yields higher-than-expected structural cost savings, operating margins and FCF could expand significantly faster than 5%.</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing Power:</strong> Continued duopoly discipline (with UPS) allowing sustained yield improvements above inflation.</li>
    <li><strong>Capex Efficiency:</strong> If peak network investments are behind them, structural reductions in capital intensity could dramatically boost FCF conversion.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Macroeconomic Recession:</strong> Logistics volumes are highly correlated with global GDP and consumer spending. A severe recession would compress top-line revenue and margins simultaneously.</li>
    <li><strong>Labor Unrest:</strong> Pilot contract negotiations and broader labor cost inflation can quickly erode operating leverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Amazon Insourcing:</strong> Increased competition from Amazon logistics expanding third-party delivery services could pressure volumes and yields.</li>
    <li><strong>Fuel Volatility:</strong> While fuel surcharges mitigate risk, rapid spikes in energy costs can create temporary margin compression and drag on volumes.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">FedEx is a cyclical, capital-intensive business heavily exposed to global economic fluctuations. A 9.5% WACC appropriately penalizes the cash flows for this inherent macroeconomic risk and accounts for the company's significant debt load, balancing against the current 10Y Treasury yield of 4.18%.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is Net Cash negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">FedEx utilizes significant debt to finance its massive global fleet of aircraft, vehicles, and sorting hubs. Total debt exceeds total cash and equivalents on the balance sheet, resulting in a negative net cash position which must be deducted from the Enterprise Value to find the Enterprise Value (actually Equity Value).</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

